```typescript
export function nextGeneration(liveCells: [number, number][]): [number, number][] {
  const liveSet = new Set(liveCells.map(([x, y]) => `${x},${y}`));
  const candidates = new Map<string, number>();
  for (const [x, y] of liveCells) {
    for (let dx = -1; dx <= 1; dx++) {
      for (let dy = -1; dy <= 1; dy++) {
        if (dx === 0 && dy === 0) continue;
        const key = `${x + dx},${y + dy}`;
        candidates.set(key, (candidates.get(key) || 0) + 1);
      }
    }
  }
  const result: [number, number][] = [];
  for (const [key, count] of candidates) {
    const isAlive = liveSet.has(key);
    if (count === 3 || (isAlive && count === 2)) {
      const [x, y] = key.split(",").map(Number);
      result.push([x, y]);
    }
  }
  return result;
}
```

The test: A cell with exactly 2 neighbors survives. Use a simple configuration like three cells in a row: [[0,0], [1,0], [2,0]]. The center cell (1,0) has 2 neighbors → survives. The end cells each have 1 neighbor → die. Dead cells (0,1),(1,1),(2,1),(0,-1),(1,-1),(2,-1) — cell (1,-1) has 2 neighbors, (1,1) has 2 neighbors — not 3, so no reproduction from just 2. Actually:
- (1,-1) neighbors: (0,0),(1,0),(2,0) → 3 neighbors → born!
- (1,1) neighbors: (0,0),(1,0),(2,0) → 3 neighbors → born!

So this is actually a blinker! nextGeneration([[0,0],[1,0],[2,0]]) = [[1,-1],[1,0],[1,1]].

For a simpler test focused on survival with 2 neighbors: use the L-shape from test 4. We already tested that. 

A better approach: use 3 cells in a line and just check that the center cell with 2 neighbors is in the result.
